\section{Rendering results}

The results page has three jobs: it shows the lecturer how many people
have answered, how those answers distribute, and which answers came in.
A classroom polling tool benefits from one extra concern that a generic
dashboard would not need: a \emph{time window} the lecturer can scope
to, so a question reused across lectures (or even across years, all
sharing the same canonical hash) can be inspected as \enquote{just this
hour} or \enquote{everything ever}.  The store already filters and
aggregates by window, so the renderer only chooses a window from the
query string, asks the store, and lays out the result.

We split the rendering into small helpers so each piece can be tested
in isolation and the pedagogical flow---read input, fetch data, lay
out output---reads from top to bottom.

\subsection{Picking the window from the query string}

The window arrives as a query-string parameter on [[/<prefix>/results]].
We allow only the strings the store accepts; anything else collapses to
[[\"all\"]] before it reaches the store, mirroring the store's own
fallback so the layers stay consistent.

<<functions>>=
def _parse_window(query_string: str) -> str:
    candidate = parse_qs(query_string).get("window", ["all"])[0]
    if candidate in {"hour", "day", "all"}:
        return candidate
    return "all"
@

<<test functions>>=
def test_parse_window_keeps_known_values_and_falls_back():
    assert server_module._parse_window("window=hour") == "hour"
    assert server_module._parse_window("window=day") == "day"
    assert server_module._parse_window("window=all") == "all"
    assert server_module._parse_window("") == "all"
    assert server_module._parse_window("window=garbage") == "all"
@

\subsection{The window filter form}

The filter is a plain [[<form method="get">]] with a [[<select>]] and
a submit button.  Three reasons to keep it boring: there is no
JavaScript elsewhere in the project, the URL stays bookmarkable, and
the existing two-second [[<meta http-equiv="refresh">]] preserves the
query string because it reloads the current URL verbatim---so the
lecturer's filter choice survives every refresh tick without us
writing any client-side state.

<<functions>>=
def _render_window_filter(prefix: str, current: str) -> str:
    options = [
        ("hour", "Last hour"),
        ("day", "Last day"),
        ("all", "All time"),
    ]
    rendered = "".join(
        f'<option value="{value}"'
        f'{" selected" if value == current else ""}>'
        f'{escape(label)}</option>'
        for value, label in options
    )
    return (
        f'<form class="window-filter" method="get" '
        f'action="/{prefix}/results">'
        f'<label for="window">Show:</label> '
        f'<select id="window" name="window">{rendered}</select> '
        f'<button type="submit">Apply</button>'
        f'</form>'
    )
@

<<test functions>>=
def test_window_filter_marks_only_the_current_selection():
    rendered = server_module._render_window_filter("abcd", "hour")
    assert 'value="hour" selected' in rendered
    assert 'value="day" selected' not in rendered
    assert 'value="all" selected' not in rendered
    assert 'action="/abcd/results"' in rendered
