\subsection{Markdown for free-text answers}

Free-text answers benefit from light formatting---emphasis, lists, code
spans, links to references---so they read as prose rather than as a wall
of plain text.  Markdown is the de-facto convention for that, and
[[markdown-it-py]] is a pure-Python CommonMark engine without external
binaries to install.

The danger of rendering user-submitted content is XSS.  We close two
common vectors:
\begin{description}
\item[Raw HTML] [[html=False]] makes the parser escape any literal
  [[<script>]], [[<iframe>]], or other tag in the input.
\item[Hostile URLs] An explicit allow-list of [[http]], [[https]], and
  [[mailto]] sits in front of the engine's default validator (which
  already blocks [[javascript:]], [[vbscript:]], [[data:]], and
  [[file:]] URLs).  Replacing the default with an explicit allow-list
  keeps the policy auditable in one place and prevents a future library
  upgrade from quietly broadening the accepted scheme set.
\end{description}
Storage stays as the raw markdown source; rendering happens only at
view time, so the JSON export remains a faithful, lossless copy of what
the student typed.

<<constants>>=
_MARKDOWN = MarkdownIt(
    "commonmark",
    {
        "html": False,
        "linkify": False,
        "typographer": False,
    },
)

_SAFE_URL_SCHEMES = {"http", "https", "mailto"}
@

The validator runs on every link the parser sees and is bound to
[[_MARKDOWN]] once at import time.  A relative URL (no colon) is
rejected: the polling server does not host arbitrary local pages, and
resolving relative links at render time is outside the threat model.

<<functions>>=
def _is_safe_url(url: str) -> bool:
    if ":" not in url:
        return False
    scheme = url.split(":", 1)[0].strip().lower()
    return scheme in _SAFE_URL_SCHEMES


_MARKDOWN.validateLink = _is_safe_url


def _render_open_answer_markdown(text: str) -> str:
    """Render a student's free-text answer as safe HTML."""
    return _MARKDOWN.render(text)
@

